User survey for ImagingSociety 2025 - National MRI research infrastructure in Norway

Author

Dr. Athanasia M. Mowinckel

Published

September 24, 2025

Background

This report presents an analysis of the survey data collected for the national grant scheme application for MRI research infrastructure in Norway. The survey was designed to gather insights from the research community on the current use, needs, and challenges related to MRI for human research.

The following sections will present a summary of the key findings, including graphical representations of the quantitative data and a textual summary of the open-ended responses, with the help of the Gemini LMM.

Survey Results

Of the 46 responses, 17 participants reported they currently use MRI for research, 37% indicate a future interest in using the new MRI facility for their work.

Participant Demographics

This section provides an overview of the survey participants’ roles and institutions.

Research Areas

The survey respondents represent a diverse range of research areas, but cognitive neuroscience and related fields like neuroscience, brain imaging, and neurology are heavily represented. Other notable areas include mental health (psychiatry, psychotherapy, and related disorders), aging/dementia, women’s health, and rehabilitation medicine. There’s also representation from more niche areas like music cognition, bilingualism, brain injury in sport, and even paleoclimatology utilizing medical imaging techniques. The unifying theme is a strong focus on the brain, cognition, and neurological function, with applications across various health conditions and demographics.

How MRI Would Enhance Research

Based on the survey responses, expanded access to MRI would significantly improve and broaden research in several key areas:

  • Enhanced Understanding of Brain Function & Disorders: Researchers across various fields (e.g., sexual dysfunction, aging, bilingualism, ADHD, eating disorders, neurological disorders, pain) would use MRI (structural and functional) to investigate the neural underpinnings of these conditions and their effects on brain structure, function, and connectivity.
  • Improved Study Design & Data Collection: Researchers emphasized the need for increased sample sizes, longitudinal studies, and multi-center collaborations.
  • Validation of Interventions & Diagnostics: MRI would be used to assess the effectiveness of clinical interventions (e.g., brain stimulation, dementia treatment) and to develop new diagnostic biomarkers (e.g., for ADHD, lupus nephritis, geohazards).
  • Advancement of Basic Research: Some responses focused on how MRI would open new avenues of basic research to understand brain function, cognition, and behavior (e.g. brain stimulation, neurochemistry, artificial agents)
  • Career Development & Funding Opportunities: Some respondents stated their lack of access to MRI has impaired their ability to conduct research, gain publications, and secure funding, despite promising research proposals.
  • Increased Availability to Participants: Respondents working in concussion research noted that participant may be intrested in MRI imaging
  • Overall: Easier access to MRI equipment would open up new possibilities for research, allowing for better access for researchers in the region and allowing for more research.

Future Needs

This section analyzes which conditions are considered most important for the future of MRI research in Norway.

Summary of Free-text Comments

This section provides a summary of the open-ended comments, generated using the Gemini LMM.

Overall, the responses highlight a desire for improved accessibility and support for MRI research. Several comments emphasize the need for dedicated research scanners, ideally located outside hospital settings and closer to university campuses, with prioritized access over clinical use. Establishing a more collaborative MRI research community, potentially across different locations like Tromsø and Bergen, is a recurring theme. Furthermore, suggestions include exploring better pricing models for research scans, ensuring consistency in scanner capabilities across sites, and establishing reliable, predictable research hours. While integrating with radiology staff might offer benefits, maintaining consistency and dedicated researcher support are seen as crucial. Mentioning existing initiatives like MMIV and acknowledging individuals like Karsten Specht could further strengthen collaborative efforts.

Conclusion

In conclusion, the overwhelming sentiment expressed in this survey underscores a significant and unmet need for increased access to dedicated research-focused MRI scanners across Norway. The responses highlight the crucial role MRI plays in diverse research areas, from understanding neurological disorders and mental health to exploring cognitive processes and even analyzing geological archives. The challenges of limited scanner availability, high costs, and logistical hurdles are demonstrably hindering Norwegian researchers’ ability to conduct cutting-edge studies, participate in multi-center collaborations, and attract vital funding. Investing in additional research MRI infrastructure, accompanied by dedicated technical and neuroradiological support, is not merely an upgrade; it is a strategic imperative that will unlock the vast potential of Norwegian researchers, accelerate scientific discovery, and ultimately improve the health and well-being of the Norwegian population and beyond. The data presented compellingly argues for prioritizing this critical investment to ensure Norway remains a competitive force in the global research landscape.
